text: Summary.  Cytorhodin-S,  an  anthracycline  derivative,  was  covalently  coupled  to  a  monoclonal  antibody  (mAb)  CA208,  against  carcinoembryonic antigen  (CEA)  in  order  to  achieve selective killing  of a  CEA-producing  colon car-  cinoma  cell  line,  COLO  205.  The  conjugate  (15  molecules  of  drugs/antibody)  retained  substantial  antibody  activity  as  well  as  drug  activity  as  assessed  by  enzyme-linked  im-  munosorbent assay and  24-h  LI210 proliferation assay, re-  spectively.  Furthermore,  the  growth  of COLO  205  cells in  a  short-term  cytostatic assay.  This  cytostatic  effect  of  the  immunoconjugate  on  COLO  205  cells  was  inhibited  in  a  dose-dependent  manner  by  pretreatment  of the  cells  with  unconjugated  CA208  mAb.  In  addition,  chloroquine,  a  lysosomotropic agent,  inhibit-  ed the cytostatic effect of the immunoconjugate, indicating  the  involvement  of  lysosomal  enzymes  in  releasing  drugs  from  the  immunoconjugate.  The  antibody  (CA208)  was  significantly  incorporated  into  the  cytoplasm  of  COLO  205  cells  as  demonstrated  by  immuno-electron  microsco-  py.  These  in  vitro  results  indicate  that  cytorhodin-S  may  be a good partner  in  immunoconjugates.  However, in vivo  animal  experiments  with  the  immunoconjugate  revealed  that  the immunoconjugate was  not  so effective in  prolong-  ing  survival.  Thus,  in  vivo  efficacy  of  this  immunocon-  jugate  remains  to  be  further  improved  in  application  to  cancer immunotherapy,

Immunoconjugates  of  antitumor  agents  such  as  drugs  [8,  31,  32],  toxins  [3,  4,  10,  20]  or  isotopes  [5,  17,  29],  coupled  to  tumor-associated-antigen-specific  antibodies  have been  extensively studied  and  are thought to be one of  the  more  advanced  potential  drug-delivery  systems  in  cancer  chemotherapy.  Generally,  anthracycline  deriva-  tives,  daunomycin  [12,  15], Adriamycin  [6] or  indarubicin  [26],  are  preferentially  used  as  the  drug  in  immunocon-  jugates  because of their broad-spectrum  antitumor  activity  [36].  However,  one  major  problem  with  these  is  that  drug  is  significantly  de-  activity  of  the  creased in most cases. Selective  killing of carcinoembryonic-antigen (CEA)-producing  cells in vitro by the immunoconjugate cytorhodin-S  and  CEA-reactive cytorhodin-S antibody CA208  Antibodies.  Murine  monoclonal  antibody  (mAb),  CA208,  established  in  our  laboratory,  reacted  with  CEA  but  not  with  other  CEA-related  antigens  such  as  non-specific  cross-reacting  antigen,  NCA-2,  «l-acid  g|ycoprotein,  or  blood  antigen  [16]. This  mAb  was  purified  from  ascitic  fluid  through  salting-out  with  45%  ammonium  sulfate,  so-  lution  in  PBS,  and  dialysis  against  the  same  buffer. ity  of  the  drug  as  weil  as  of  the  antibody.  In  order  to  achieve selective killing  of carcinoembryonic-antigen-pro-  ducing  target  COLO  205  cells,  cytorhodin-S  (Cyt-S),  an  anthracycline  derivative [18,  19], was  coupled  to  a  mono-  clonal  carcinoembryonic  antigen  (CEA)  [16]. First,  the  Cyt-S-CA208  conjugate was  evaluated for both the pharmacological activity of the drug  and  the  immunological  activity of the  antibody.  Second,  a  possible  mechanism(s)  of the  selective effect of the  immu-  noconjugate  on  target  cells  was  investigated  biologically  by treating cells with a  lysosomotropic agent,  chloroquine,  and  by morphological  immuno-electron microscopy.  The  present  data  clearly  show  that  (a)  Cyt-S-CA208  conjugate weil retains both  drug  and  immunological activ-  ity,  (b)  the  immunoconjugate  is  efficiently  incorporated  into  COLO  205  cells,  and  that  (c)  it  is  effective in  killing  CEA-producing  tumor  cells in  vitro.  Cytorhodin-S.  Cytorhodin-S  was  prepared  by  the  acid  treatment  of a  crude  cytorhodin mixture produced  by cul-  tivating  Streptomyces  Y-11472  (deposition  no.  DSM-2658)  [19].  Cytorhodin-S  (purity,  98%)  was  kindly  supplied  by  Dr.  Sedlacek (Behringwerke AG,  FRG).

Cell  lines.  COLO  205  (human  colon  carcinoma)  [28],  COLO  201  (human  colon  carcinoma)  [28], A549  (human  lung  carcinoma)  [13] and  K-562  (human  chronic myeloge-  neous  leukemia) [22] were purchased  from American  Type  Culture  Collection  (Rockville,  Mal), All  the  cell lines  were  maintained  in  RPMI  1640  (Nissui,  Japan)  supplemented  with  10%  heat-inactivated  fetal  bovine  serum  (Gibco,  USA) and  2 mM  glutamine (Sigma,  USA) in  5% CO2 in air  at 37°C  and  were routinely passaged  twice a  week.  ~ancer  ~!~mmunolggy  ~mmunotherapy  ©  Springer-Verlag 1989  Fig. 1. Preparation  of cytorhodin-S and CA208 mAb conjugate.  Pu-  rified  cytorhodin-S  (10  mg)  was  treated  with  ammonium  acetate  (5.8  mg;  Aldrich  Chemical  Co.,  USA)  and  sodium  cyanoborohydride  (1.4  mg;  Nakarai  Chemical  Co.,  Japan)  in  2 ml  absolute  methanol  with  stirring  for  4 h  at  room  temperature  in the  dark.  The  reaction  mixture  was  applied  on  HPLC  with  C18  reverse-phase  chromatography  (sol-  vent;  2.0%  triethylammonium  phosphate,  pH  3.0,  acetoni-  trile  linear  gradient  0%--30% column;  Senshupak  NP-318,  10 mm  x  250  mm).  Fractions  corresponding  to  amino  cy-  torhodin-S  were  pooled.  Acetonitrile  was  removed  from  this  solution  under  reduced  pressure  and  the  residue  was  passed  through  Sep-pak  C18  (Waters,  USA)  for  desalting  and  concentration.

To  1 ml  of  a  solution  containing  IgG  (18 mg)  (CA208  mAb  or  nIgG  as  a  control)  in  50 mM  phosphate  buffer  with  1 mM  EDTA,  pH  7.5  (buffer A),  10 ~tl 100 mM  N-suc-  cinimidyl-S-acetylthioacetate  (SATA;  Behring  Diagnos-  tics,  USA)  [7]  in  N,N-dimethylformamide  was  added  and  the  mixture  was  stirred  for  20  min  at  room  temperature.  After the  addition  of 50  gl  1 M  TRIS/HC1  (pH  7.8)  to  stop  the  reaction,  the  mixture  was  subjected  to  a  gel  filtration  on  a  PD-10  column  (Pharmacia,  Sweden)  in  buffer  A  to  obtain  SATA-IgG  conjugates.  Hydroxylamine  (0.5  mM)  in buffer A, corresponding  to  50 mol equivalents  of SATA,  was  added  to  the  solution  of  SATA-IgG  conjugates  for  deacetylation  at  room  temperature  for  1 h.  GMBS-Cyt-S  (24 mg)  in  dimethylformamide was  added  to  this  aqueous  solution  containing  IgG  with  free  thiol  groups,  followed  by  stirring  for  24 h  at  4°C  in  the  dark.  The  reaction  mix-  ture  was  applied  on  a  Sephadex  G-50  (Pharmacia,  Swe-  den)  column  (25  mm  x  400  mm)  equilibrated  with  buffer  A. Antibody  activity  of  the  immunoconjugate,  mAb  activity  against  CEA  remaining  after  conjugation  was  determined  by  enzyme-linked  immunosorbent  assay  (ELISA)  [16] car-  ried  out  in  duplicate.  Purified  CEA  (50  I.tl at  50  txg/ml)  in  0.01  M  PBS  was  coated  on  a  96-well  microtiter  plate  at  room  temperature  for  1 h.  The  plate  was  incubated  with  1% bovine serum  albumin  in  PBS  for  1 h  at room tempera-  ture  for  blocking.  Thereafter,  40  ktl  immunoconjugate  or  unconjugated  antibody  was  added  and  the  plate  was  kept  for  1 h  at  room  temperature.  After  washing,  40  ~tl  horse-  radish-peroxidase-conjugated  rabbit  anti-(mouse  immuno-  globulin)  was  added,  and  the plate was again  kept  at room  temperature  for  1 h.  After  washing,  40  pJ  o-phenylen e-  diamine  (1  mg/tal)  in  0.1  M  citrate  buffer  (pH  5.0)  con-  taining  0.006%  H202 was  added  to  each  weil  and  the  plate  was  incubated  for  15 min.  The  reaction  was terminated  by  the  addition  of  40  ~tl  2 M  H2SO4.  The  absorbance  at  490  nm  was measured  by using  a  micro-ELISA autoreader  (Dynatech,  USA).

Drug activity  of the imrnunoconjugate.  Pharmacological  ac-  tivity of the  Cyt-S-CA208  conjugate was  assessed by a  [3H]  thymidine  incorporation  assay employing two different in-  cubation  periods.  (a)  For  the  24-h  inhibition  assay,  200  ~tl  cell suspension  (105 cells/ml) was added  to a flat-bottomed  microtiter plate,  and  free cytorhodin-S  or the  immunocon-  jugate  (10  lxl  each)  was  added  to  the  cells.  This  was  per-  formed  in  quadruplicate.  Control  wells  received  10  ~tl  growth  medium  and  the  cells  were  cultured  at  37°C  for  18 h.  To  label  cellular  DNA,  25/xl  [3H]thymidine  (20  ~tCi/  ml)  was  added.  After  6 h  incubation  the  cells  were  har-  reacted  with  N-y-maleimidobutylyloxysuccinimide  3.8  mg;  Behring  Diagnostics,  USA)  [11,  33],  in  5 ml  dry  pyridine  with  stirring  for  2 h  at  room  temperature  in  the  dark.  The  reaction  mixture  was  applied  on  HPLC  as  described  above.  GMBS-Cyt-S  was  lyophilized  and  stored  in  the  dark  at  -  20 ° C.

The  incorpo-  rated  radioactivities  were measured  in  a  liquid  scintillation  counter  (Beckman  LS  3801,  Beckman,  USA).  (b)  For  the  short-term  inhibition  assay,  1 ml  cells  (10 a  cells/m!)  was  dispensed  into  sterile  polystyrene  tubes  and  incubated  with  the  free  drug  or  immunoconjugate  for  30-120  min  at  37°C.  The cells were then  washed three times with  PBS,  re-  suspended  in growth  medium,  and  200-~tl aliquots  pipetted  onto  microtiter  plates,  in  quadruplicate,  for  an  18-h  incu-  for  bation.  The  cells  were  then  pulsed  with  3Hthymidine  6 h,  harvested,  and  the  incorporated  radioactivities  were  measured  as  described  above.  Incorporation  of  SHthy-  midine  was  expressed  as the  percentage  inhibition jn  com-  parison  to  the  incorporation  of 3Hthymidine  by  controls.  The  standard  error  was  computed  using  quadruplicate  de-  terminations,  and  was  less  than  5%  at  any  given  experi-  mental  point.

Inhibition  of cytostatic  effect  of the  immunoconjugate  with  unconjugated  mAb. Then  the  cells  were  pulse-labeled  with  3Hthy-  midine  for  6 h  before  harvesting,  and  the  incorporated  radioactivities  were  measured  in  the  liquid  scintillation  counter. In  vivo animal  experiments  with  an  intraperitoneal  thera-  peutic  trial  with  the  immunoconjugate.  COLO  205  cells  (5 ×  10 6  cells)  were  inoculated  i.p.  into  6-7-week-old  fe-  male  nude  mice of BALB/c  origin.  The test  samples  at the  equivalent  dose  of  3 lxg  cytorhodin-S  were  injected  i.p.  into  five  different  groups  consisting  of  six  mice  each  on  days  1,  3,  5,  7  and  9.  The  5 x  10 6 COLO  205  cells  were  the  minimum  number  required  for the  formation  of tumors  in  injected  nude  mice.  Binding  of  the  immunoconjugate  to  CEA  was  mea-  sured  by  ELISA.  Cyt-S-CA208  conjugate  retained  anti-  body  activity  at  a  satisfactory  level  compared  with  that  of  CA208  mAb  alone  (Fig.  2).  On  the  other  hand,  the  drug  activity  of the  conjugates  was  measured  by a  24-h  L1210 proliferation  assay (Fig.  3).  Both  Cyt-S-CA208  and  Cyt-S-nIgG  conjugates  satisfac-  torily  retained  drug  activity after conjugation.  The  median  inhibitory  doses  (IC»0)  of  cytorhodin-S  alone,  Cyt-  S-CA208  conjugate,  and  Cyt-S-nIgG  conjugate  were  20,  29  and  24 nM  respectively  (average  of  two  experiments).  Statistical analysis.  The data  of in vivo animal  experiments  was  analyzed  by  Student's  t-test.

The  cy-  tostatic  effect of the  conjugate  was  inhibited  by  50% in  the  presence  of  chloroquine.  Therefore,  effective  conjugation  between  drug  and  antibody  is  required  to  render  the  con-  jugate  more  susceptible  to  the  lysosomal  enzymes,  as  de-  scribed  previously [9,  30,  34,  35].

Since  we  had  obtained  good  results,  i.e.  specific  and  significant  accumulation  of radiolabeled  CA208  mAb  into  CEA-producing  tumors  implanted  in  nude  mice  in  a  tumor-imaging study  (unpublished  data),  we  performed  in  vivo  therapeutic  experiments  using  COLO205-bearing  nude  mice.  Treatment  with  cytorhodin-S  alone  and  with  a  mixture of cytorhodin-S  and  CA208  mAb  actually resulted  in  a  decreased  survival period  as  compared  to  the  control.  Reasons  for  this  might  include  toxic  side-effects  of  the  drug.  However,  the  Cyt-S-CA208  conjugate  obviously  prolonged  the  survival period  more  than  in  trials  with  cy-  torhodin-S  alone,  the  cytorhodin-S  CA208  mAb  mixture  or  Cyt-S-nIgG  conjugate,  but  was  not  as  effective  as  we  had  anticipated  (Fig.  10). There may be several reasons  for  the  decreased  effectiveness  of  the  immunoconjugate  in  vivo. (a)  Immunocomplex formation  of the  conjugate with  circulating  CEA  secreted  from  tumor  cells  is  possible;  in  general,  secretion  of tumor-associated  antigens  may signif-  icantly  diminish  the  amount  of  conjugate  that  actually  reaches  target  cells.  (b)  Rapid  break  down  might  occur  with  a  short  half-life  of the  immunoconjugate  in  the  host  body  fluid.  The  administered  immunoconjugate  is  so  rap-  idly  broken  down  that  side-effects  of  the  resultant  freely  circulating  cytorhodin-S  may be  observed  in  host  mice.

We  have  developed  a  new  conjugation  method,  and  the immunoconjugate  obtained  by this  method  retains  well  both  drug  and  antibody  binding  activities.  Although  it  is  necessary  to  elucidate  and  solve  the  problems  described  above  orte  by  one,  cytorhodin-S  is  a  good  partner  in  the  immunoconjugate,  and  its  conjugation  with  antibodies  of  higher  specificity  and  less  crossreactivity will  enable  us  to  carry  out  specific immunotherapy  in  the  near  future  [1,  2].
